      "text": "Zoo-keeper Approach",
      "fontSize": 28,
      "fontFamily": 5,
      "textAlign": "left",
      "verticalAlign": "top",
      "containerId": null,
      "originalText": "Zoo-keeper Approach",
      "autoResize": true,
      "lineHeight": 1.25
    },
    {
      "id": "sz90E5bQKMTdec2HpaYUY",
      "type": "text",
      "x": 1993.2250248427792,
      "y": 1082.399661881853,
      "width": 497.05791285976466,
      "height": 525,
      "angle": 0,
      "strokeColor": "#1e1e1e",
      "backgroundColor": "transparent",
      "fillStyle": "solid",
      "strokeWidth": 2,
      "strokeStyle": "solid",
      "roughness": 1,
      "opacity": 100,
      "groupIds": [],
      "frameId": null,
      "index": "aq",
      "roundness": null,
      "seed": 2022597028,
      "version": 1768,
      "versionNonce": 404408732,
      "isDeleted": false,
      "boundElements": [],
      "updated": 1782629544922,
      "link": null,
      "locked": false,
      "text": "Zoo keeper basically assignes each server a\nparticular ID range, this is how uniqueness is\nensured currently.\n\nAgain if this is a SPOF multiple instances of\nZookeeper can be maintained\n\nIf a zookeeper fails the moment request comes,\nthat range is dropped and the next range is\nassigned when it becomes available again. since we\nhave around 3.5 Trillion available unique URLs this\nis enough even if a 1 mil range is dropped.\n\n\nAlso the Zookeeper will have less frequent calls to\nsince a server will only reach out to it when its 1\nmil range is over. Unlike in case of count cache\nwhere the server just reaches out for each id\ncausing collisions.\n\nServers have seperate pools assigned to pick from.",
      "fontSize": 20,
      "fontFamily": 5,
      "textAlign": "left",
      "verticalAlign": "top",
      "containerId": null,
      "originalText": "Zoo keeper basically assignes each server a particular ID range, this is how uniqueness is ensured currently.\n\nAgain if this is a SPOF multiple instances of Zookeeper can be maintained\n\nIf a zookeeper fails the moment request comes, that range is dropped and the next range is assigned when it becomes available again. since we have around 3.5 Trillion available unique URLs this is enough even if a 1 mil range is dropped.\n\n\nAlso the Zookeeper will have less frequent calls to since a server will only reach out to it when its 1 mil range is over. Unlike in case of count cache where the server just reaches out for each id causing collisions.\n\nServers have seperate pools assigned to pick from.",
      "autoResize": false,
      "lineHeight": 1.25
    },
